I think this is closed to the preferred style:
```suggestion
instance : Star (CentroidHom Î±) where
  star f :=
  { toFun := fun a => star (f (star a))
    map_zero' := by
      simp only [star_zero, map_zero]
    map_add' := fun a b => by simp only [star_add, map_add]
    map_mul_left' := fun a b => by simp only [star_mul, map_mul_right, star_star]
    map_mul_right' := fun a b => by simp only [star_mul, map_mul_left, star_star] }
```
This and `star_add` doesn't need commutativity; can you promote the instance above to `StarAddMonoid`?

Is your proposal that we change the definition of `CentroidHom` from
```
structure CentroidHom (Î± : Type*) [NonUnitalNonAssocSemiring Î±] extends Î± â†’+ Î± where...
```
to
```
structure CentroidHom (Î± : Type*) [AddMonoid Î±] [Mul Î±] extends Î± â†’+ Î± where...
```
?
Not at all, it's that you add a separate `StarAddMonoid (CentroidHom Î±)` instance which won't need commutativity.

Can you add a docstring that states that `star f a = star (f (star a))` (or in $\LaTeX$ if you prefer), and gives a reference for this definition? I've seen a handful of cases where there's no obvious canonical star structure, which a reference would allay any concerns over.

@eric-wieser I've been thinking about this. I haven't been able to find a precise reference, but from my perspective, this is a consequence of a *-ring being a *-triple. The definition of a centroid homomorphism `T` on a *-triple requires the existence of another map `T^*`, and a mild condition can be placed on the *-triple guaranteeing uniqueness of `T^*`. In the case of a *-triple generated from a *-ring, the algebraic centroid is a *-subalgebra of the triple centroid. A further mild condition makes them coincide. The involution I've defined here coincides with the triple centroid one when the uniqueness condition is in force.

Perhaps a better approach than this PR would be for me to develop the theory outlined above in Mathlib and then treat this as a special case?
Furthermore, this definition makes the natural (iso|homo)morphism defined in #7843 into a *-(iso|homo)morphism.
Can you add that  (iso|homo)morphism result to this PR?

> I've seen a handful of cases where there's no obvious canonical star structure

It seems that the canonical star structure is on the centre of the centroid (the definition works on the whole centroid, but results in an involution that doesn't satisfy the `star_mul` condition, and therefore isn't very useful).

I've added the definition of the *-homomorphsim of the centre into the centre of the centroid now.
